# Semantic Z-Sorting & Visual Hierarchy

## Problem

The current renderer sorts units with only a basic `flying` check — everything else draws in arbitrary order. This means the Oni Boss or Onmyoji can be completely buried inside a wall of Ikki Rebels. A player can't parse the threat landscape in 200ms, breaking the God-Game fantasy.

Additionally, every cavalry hit triggers `screenShake`, so 15 simultaneous cavalry charges create a strobe effect, causing eye fatigue and destroying readability.

## Resolved Design Decisions

- **Rebel alpha**: Keep full opacity. Rebels are already tiny (radius 10); layer ordering alone handles their visual hierarchy.
- **Y-sort direction**: Confirmed — **higher Y draws on top** (player defends at bottom, enemies approach from top).
- **Yumi Archers stay Layer 2** (not chaff): The doc analysis placed archers with rebels, but player archers are high-value targets — demoting them to layer 1 would make it harder for the player to notice when they're under threat. They remain standard soldiers.

## The Core Idea: Semantic Rendering Layers

Assign each unit a `renderLayer` integer in its definition. The renderer uses this as the primary sort key, Y-position as tiebreaker within each layer.

| Layer | Units | Role |
|-------|-------|------|
| `0` | Bamboo Barricade | Structures — painted on ground, always under combatants |
| `1` | Ikki Rebel, Tengu Flier | Chaff — drawn first, visually recede naturally |
| `2` | Yumi, Horoku, Hatamoto, Onmyoji, Shinobi | Standard soldiers |
| `3` | Cavalry, Champion | Elites — spear protrusions must read above melee |
| `4` | Great Oni | Boss — mathematically impossible to be buried |

